Date: Thu, 27 Jun 1996 20:20:35 +-1000
From: Andrew Padula <amp@ne.com.au>
Via: "Veterinary professionals list" <vetplus-l@u.washington.edu>
Subject: RE: Paralysed cats update
Have you thought about hypokalaemia as a cause of your paralysis. I
have seen lots of cats that respond to K+ supplements with generalised
weakness and paralysis. Some commercial foods cause the urine pH to be
too high and promote loss of K+ ions and thus clinical hypokalaemia. It
can come on very quickly but in it must take some time to deplete total
body k+ reserves.
---
Andrew Padula BVSc(Hons), MRCVS.
Geelong, Australia.
